# BROKER_MODE is read by up.sh to select this strategy file.
# It is NOT injected into containers — it is a launcher-only variable.
BROKER_MODE=kafka

# WHY: Kafka provides ordered, durable, high-throughput message delivery.
# Ideal for event-driven architectures, log aggregation, data pipelines,
# analytics event ingestion, and audit trail processing.
#
# Architecture:
#   Kafka (KRaft mode, no ZooKeeper) handles message brokering.
#   Redis remains active as the Celery result backend — Kafka does not
#   support result storage natively.
#
# Use when: High-throughput streaming workloads, event sourcing, ordered
# processing within partitions, or when your team already operates Kafka
# infrastructure and wants a unified messaging layer.
#
# Trade-offs vs Redis:
#   + Durable by default (messages persist to disk)
#   + Ordered delivery within partitions
#   + Horizontal scaling via partition assignment
#   - Higher latency than Redis for small messages
#   - More resource-intensive (CPU + disk I/O)
#
# Trade-offs vs RabbitMQ:
#   + Higher raw throughput for streaming workloads
#   + Built-in log compaction and replay
#   + Partition-based parallelism (vs queue-based)
#   - No per-message acknowledgment (offset-based commits)
#   - No native dead-letter queue (requires application-level handling)
